# Comprehensive Report on How Slavery Ended

## Introduction

Slavery, a system where individuals are owned and forced to work without consent, has been a tragic and pervasive institution throughout human history. The abolition of slavery was a complex, multifaceted process influenced by economic, political, social, and humanitarian factors that unfolded over centuries and across continents. This report provides an in-depth, structured analysis of how slavery ended, focusing primarily on the United States while also considering global contexts. It draws upon historical events, legislative milestones, social movements, and economic changes, supported by reliable and recent scholarly sources.

---

## Historical Context of Slavery

Slavery existed in various forms since ancient times, including in Mesopotamia, Egypt, Greece, and Rome, where slaves were often war captives or debtors. In the Americas, slavery became integral to the economy, particularly in the Southern United States, where plantation agriculture relied heavily on enslaved African labor. By 1861, the U.S. slave population had grown to approximately four million, primarily in the South ([Study.com](https://study.com/academy/lesson/what-is-the-13th-amendment-summary-definition-ratification.html)).

---

## Key Factors Leading to the End of Slavery

### 1. Moral and Humanitarian Opposition

The abolitionist movement, rooted in religious and moral opposition to slavery, played a pivotal role. Groups such as the Quakers and evangelical Christians, energized by the Second Great Awakening, condemned slavery as immoral and unchristian. Influential abolitionists like Frederick Douglass and Harriet Tubman galvanized public opinion against slavery ([StudyCorgi, 2021](https://studycorgi.com/history-transnational-labor-slavery-and-revolt/)).

### 2. Economic Changes

Economic factors also contributed significantly. The industrializing North opposed the expansion of slavery into new territories, fearing competition with slave labor. Conversely, the Southern economy remained dependent on slavery for plantation agriculture. Over time, global economic shifts and the rise of industrial capitalism made slavery less profitable and sustainable ([Nya Bruce, 2022](https://www.study.com/academy/lesson/what-factors-led-to-the-abolition-of-slavery.html)).

### 3. Political Actions and Legislation

Political developments were crucial in ending slavery. The U.S. Constitution initially protected slavery indirectly, but over time, laws such as the Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves (1807) and state-level abolition laws chipped away at the institution. The election of Abraham Lincoln in 1860, who opposed slavery's expansion, precipitated the secession of Southern states and the Civil War ([History on the Net, 2022](https://www.historyonthenet.com/when-did-slavery-end-in-the-u-s)).

### 4. The Civil War and Emancipation

The Civil War (1861â€“1865) was the decisive conflict that led to slavery's abolition in the U.S. Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation (1863) declared slaves in rebelling states free, though it did not apply to Union-controlled areas. The war's outcome paved the way for constitutional abolition ([Study.com](https://study.com/academy/lesson/what-is-the-13th-amendment-summary-definition-ratification.html)).

