## The 13th Amendment: Legal Abolition of Slavery

The 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, ratified on December 6, 1865, legally abolished slavery and involuntary servitude, except as punishment for crime. It was the culmination of years of political struggle and war, making the abolition permanent and nationwide:

| Amendment | Date Ratified | Key Provision |
|------------|----------------|----------------|
| 13th Amendment | December 6, 1865 | "Neither slavery nor involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted, shall exist within the United States, or any place subject to their jurisdiction." |

The amendment required ratification by 27 of the 36 states at the time. Northern states ratified quickly, while Southern states followed during Reconstruction, with Mississippi being the last in 1995 ([Study.com](https://study.com/academy/lesson/what-is-the-13th-amendment-summary-definition-ratification.html)).

---

## Post-Abolition Challenges and the Black Codes

Despite legal abolition, African Americans faced systemic oppression. Southern states enacted Black Codes to restrict freed slaves' rights and maintain a labor force through vagrancy laws and convict leasing, exploiting the 13th Amendment's exception clause for criminal punishment. This effectively perpetuated a form of involuntary servitude ([David Kenneth, 2019](https://www.thoughtco.com/what-happened-after-slavery-ended-4112569)).

---

## Further Constitutional Amendments and Civil Rights

To counteract the Black Codes and ensure civil rights, Congress passed the 14th and 15th Amendments:

| Amendment | Ratification Date | Purpose |
|------------|--------------------|---------|
| 14th Amendment | July 9, 1868 | Granted citizenship to all persons born or naturalized in the U.S., including former slaves. |
| 15th Amendment | February 3, 1870 | Prohibited denying the right to vote based on race, color, or previous condition of servitude. |

However, Supreme Court decisions like the Civil Rights Cases (1883) limited federal enforcement against private discrimination, allowing segregation and disenfranchisement to persist until the Civil Rights Movement of the 20th century ([David Kenneth, 2019](https://www.thoughtco.com/what-happened-after-slavery-ended-4112569)).

